{
  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain Iqbal's 'Tarana-e-Hindi' (also known as 'Sāre Jahāñ se Acchā'), nor its famous opening line \"Sāre jahāñ se acchā Hindostāñ hamārā\" (\"Better than the entire world is our Hindostan\").**\n\nIqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* (in three parts) is present, including nationalist poems like **Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet** (*Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 26), which praises Hindustan as the poet's homeland (\"mera watan wohi hai\") through references to Chishti, Nanak, Hijaz, Greeks, Persians, Arabs, Moses, Noah, and Sinai—but lacks the specific phrasing or explicit claim of being \"the best land in the world.\" Its opening (transliteration):  \n> Chishti ne jis zameen mein paigham-e-haq sunaya  \n> Nanak ne jis chaman mein wahdat ka geet gaya[^1]\n\n**Tarana-e-Milli** (*Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23) is also here, a companion piece with \"Hindostan hamara,\" but again, a distinct Muslim-focused anthem opening \"Cheen o Arab hamara, Hindostan hamara.\"[^2]\n\nNo other Iqbal works match; if this poem exists under another title, it did not surface via searches or chapter listings.",
